@flexiarg pattern-coherence/scope-boundaries
@title Declare Scope Boundaries and Non-Goals
@sigils [üìê/‰ªÅ]
@keywords scope, boundary, limit, apply, exclude, assumption, domain, relevant, misuse, non-goal
@audience pattern authors, reviewers
@tone technical
@style pattern

! conclusion: A good pattern defines where it applies and where it should not be used.
  + context: Patterns drift into slogans when boundaries are missing, leading to misuse outside their intended domain.
  + IF:
    The pattern reads as universally true or lacks explicit limits.
  + HOWEVER:
    Overly narrow boundaries can make a useful pattern seem irrelevant.
  + THEN:
    State at least one inclusion boundary (when it applies) and one exclusion boundary (when it does not).
    Name the assumptions the pattern relies on (constraints, environment, actors, or scale).
  + BECAUSE:
    Clear boundaries prevent category errors and let readers decide quickly whether to apply the pattern.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - evidence: an application within the stated scope that succeeds.
    - evidence: a near-scope case that fails and justifies the exclusion boundary.
    - evidence-shape: {:applies-when [:string], :does-not-apply-when [:string], :assumptions [:string], :scope/example :string, :anti-scope/example :string}
